GIving them the contact information of
any of the people that they need to be

15
00:00:49.550 --> 00:00:52.250
in contact with,
throughout the entire process.

16
00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:54.020
And then,
establishing any sort of policies.

17
00:00:54.020 --> 00:00:57.460
So, often, it makes a lot of
sense to set up policies for

18
00:00:57.460 --> 00:01:00.270
how you're gonna interact
with the internal team.

19
00:01:00.270 --> 00:01:02.365
How are you going to
communicate with them?

20
00:01:02.365 --> 00:01:05.990
What's okay and what's not okay
in terms of feedback and review?

21
00:01:05.990 --> 00:01:08.370
The same sort of thing for
external interactions.

22
00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.340
So, how are you gonna
interact with other people?

23
00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:13.940
Is that all gonna flow through
the management of the data science team?

24
00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:18.790
Or is that gonna be embedding people
briefly in other teams during the week?

25
00:01:18.790 --> 00:01:20.220
And how are they gonna
communicate with them?

26
00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:23.190
All of that needs to be laid out,
ideally in a short,

27
00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:26.900
initial meeting where they actually get
all that information sort of compressed.

28
00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:31.310
It's really ideal if that information
could be stored somewhere internally

29
00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:35.260
on a level that they can communicate with.

30
00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:38.350
Whether it's a website, or some kind
of document that's distributed, so

31
00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:40.810
that they actually can
always have a reference for

32
00:01:40.810 --> 00:01:43.900
who they should be contacting,
how they should be acting, and so forth.

33
00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:46.880
So, that's the ideal way to make sure
that they always have that information

34
00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:48.260
available to them.

35
00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:51.730
The next step is usually human resources,
so they need to get set up with payroll.

36
00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:55.360
They need to get set up with benefits,
any kind of documentation they need.

37
00:01:55.360 --> 00:01:57.710
So this isn't really part of
the data science process, but

38
00:01:57.710 --> 00:02:01.630
it is always a step that needs to happen
in the onboarding process for people.

39
00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:03.700
Then the next thing that needs
to happen is introductions.

40
00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:05.720
And so
that person might have interviewed, and

41
00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:08.140
you might have even be aware
that they're showing up.

42
00:02:08.140 --> 00:02:12.210
But it's really good to have that
person be able to go around and

43
00:02:12.210 --> 00:02:15.730
put a face to the name for all
the people within the data science team.

44
00:02:15.730 --> 00:02:19.334
So this is ideal if you, as the manager,
can go and take them from place to place,

45
00:02:19.334 --> 00:02:22.779
introduce them to all the data science
team, make sure they get to know them,

46
00:02:22.779 --> 00:02:24.581
they have a few minutes to talk, and so,

47
00:02:24.581 --> 00:02:27.960
that everybody knows who
the new member of the team is.

48
00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:31.130
You also might want to introduce them
their external points of contact.

49
00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:34.748
Whatever external units they'll be working
